 uld Hall (GLD)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:Gould G
 allery
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:cbeevents@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="CBE Categories";ID=60249;TYPE=CustomAsset:Arc
 hitecture\,Construction Management\,Landscape Architecture\,Real Estate
 \,Research\,Urban Design & Planning
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Exhibi
 ts
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgBg5GDujMoh0DX2ZyHWVVO5.jpg
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:Dept.
  of Landscape Architecture: https://larch.be.uw.edu/\nCollege of Built E
 nvironments: https://be.uw.edu/
DTSTAMP:20260401T113836Z
DESCRIPTION:Event Interval: Ongoing event\nCampus location: Gould Hall (
 GLD)\nCampus room: Gould Gallery\nAccessibility Contact: cbeevents@uw.ed
 u\nCBE Categories: Architecture\,Construction Management\,Landscape Arch
 itecture\,Real Estate\,Research\,Urban Design & Planning\nEvent Types: E
 xhibits\nEvent sponsors: <a href="https://larch.be.uw.edu/" target="_bla
 nk">Dept. of Landscape Architecture</a><br /><a href="https://be.uw.edu/
 " target="_blank">College of Built Environments</a>\n\nDesigning\, Craft
 ing and Building Community represents a reflective “looking back” over t
 hirty years since the design / build model was embedded into the Departm
 ent of Landscape Architecture’s Bachelor of Landscape Architecture (BLA)
  program at the University of Washington. \n\nAs a unique model of teach
 ing\, learning and community service\, the exhibition includes voices of
  past and current participants\, and shows the narrative of its evolutio
 n. \n\nAt the heart of this program\, design / build addresses issues of
  social justice\, green building\, ecological and sustainable design and
  supporting students to explore materials\, forms\, and responsive desig
 n. Employing multimedia\, this immersive exhibition is a mosaic illustra
 ting the diversity of projects\, community partners\, student experience
 s\, and award-winning projects.\n\nThe exhibition will be on view April 
 1-May 1\, 2026\, and is free and open to the public. Visitors are welcom
 e Monday through Friday from 10:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m.\n\nThe reception fo
 r this exhibit will be held April 14th from 6-8 pm. Registration opens M
 arch 12th.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
