BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:EXHIBIT: Reimagining Korean Jogakbo: From Tradition to Sustainab
 ility
LOCATION:Gowen Hall (GWN)
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260406
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260501
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:TRUE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Ong
 oing event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:Go
 wen Hall (GWN)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:Tateuch
 i East Asia Library\, George M. Beckmann Reading Room (Gowen 3rd)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:hkyi@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Exhibi
 ts
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgDhKyAI7u6Pqt3JkMU3u1HR.jpg
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:Tateu
 chi East Asia Library
DTSTAMP:20260403T094312Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Ongoing event\nCampus location: Gowen Hall (
 GWN)\nCampus room: Tateuchi East Asia Library\, George M. Beckmann Readi
 ng Room (Gowen 3rd)\nAccessibility Contact: hkyi@uw.edu\nEvent Types: Ex
 hibits\nEvent sponsors: Tateuchi East Asia Library\n\nThe Tateuchi East 
 Asia Library: \nhttps://lib.uw.edu/location/tateuchi-east-asia-library/ 
 at the University of Washington invites the public to visit Reimagining 
 Korean Jogakbo: From Tradition to Sustainability\, on view April 6-30\, 
 2026\, in the Reading Room exhibit cases at the Tateuchi Library\, featu
 ring works by Bella Youngok Kim. \n\n\nReimagining Korean Jogakbo: From 
 Tradition to Sustainability introduces Jogakbo\, a traditional Korean wr
 apping cloth made from small fabric remnants. Created by women in the ho
 usehold\, Jogakbo reflects resourcefulness\, care\, and the beauty of ev
 eryday materials.\n\n\nInspired by this tradition\, Bella Yongok Kim rei
 nterprets Jogakbo through contemporary art using recycled plastic packag
 ing and fabric. By stitching together discarded materials\, she transfor
 ms what was once overlooked into new patterns and forms.\n\n\nThrough th
 is exhibition\, visitors can explore the historical roots of Jogakbo and
  its connection to sustainability\, while discovering how traditional id
 eas continue to inspire contemporary artistic practice.\n\n**Meet the ar
 tist on opening day Monday April 6 from 4-5 p.m. for questions and a bri
 ef coversation of her exhibit.**\n \n\nArtist Bio\n\nBella Yongok Kim is
  a mixed media and fiber artist based in Gig Harbor\, Washington. Born a
 nd raised in Korea\, she studied fiber art and design at Ewha Womans Uni
 versity. Her work is inspired by Korean textile traditions\, especially 
 Jogakbo\, and explores themes of sustainability\, memory\, and transform
 ation.\n \n\nKim creates artworks using recycled materials such as plast
 ic packaging and fabric scraps\, stitching them together with a sewing m
 achine to form new patterns and textures. She has exhibited widely\, inc
 luding at the Bainbridge Island Museum of Art\, Whatcom Museum\, the Nor
 thwest Quilt & Fiber Art Museum\, and the Cheongju International Craft B
 iennale in Korea. Kim is a recipient of the Artist Trust GAP Award\, rec
 ognition from the Korean American Coalition\, and her work is held in th
 e Burke Museum collection.\n\nThrough her practice\, she invites viewers
  to reconsider the value of everyday materials and the creative possibil
 ities of reuse. \n \n\nFor more info is available at Bellakim.com: https
 ://www.bellakim.com/
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
