BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Physical Chemistry Seminar: Prof. Colin Heyes
LOCATION:Chemistry Building (CHB)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260408T113000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260408T123000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
URL:https://cheyes.hosted.uark.edu/
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:Ch
 emistry Building (CHB)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:CHB 102
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:chem59x@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Academ
 ics\,Lectures/Seminars
DTSTAMP:20260403T122344Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Chemistry
  Building (CHB)\nCampus room: CHB 102\nAccessibility Contact: chem59x@uw
 .edu\nEvent Types: Academics\,Lectures/Seminars\nLink: https://cheyes.ho
 sted.uark.edu/\n\n"Structure-Optoelectronic Property Relationships in Te
 rnary and Quaternary Copper-(Zinc)-Indium Chalcogenide Quantum Dots."\nP
 rofessor Colin Heyes - Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry\, Univer
 sity of Arkansas\nHost: Tristan Shi\n\n Ternary I-III-VI quantum dots (Q
 Ds)\, such as CuInE2 (E= S\, Se) have unique optical properties for a wi
 de range of applications\, including bioimaging\, photovoltaics and opto
 electronics with the added advantage of being less toxic and less enviro
 nmentally problematic than alternative QDs. As with most QDs\, the optic
 al properties are significantly improved by the addition of a “shell”\, 
 usually consisting of a wide bandgap II-VI material\, such as ZnE. Howev
 er\, a blue shift in the emission spectra is observed upon shelling\, ra
 ther than the typical red-shift observed in other QDs\, which results fr
 om some degree of ion exchange and/or interfacial alloying in addition t
 o shelling. This process leads to a mixture of ternary and quaternary co
 mposition that is still poorly understood. The degree of ion exchange de
 pends strongly on the synthesis conditions. In this talk\, I will discus
 s how the balance of ion exchange\, alloying and shelling affects the op
 tical properties such as quantum yield\, emission spectral shape\, blink
 ing and emission lifetimes. Comparing the ensemble and single particle o
 ptical properties allows us to probe how charge carrier trapping/de-trap
 ping and exciton recombination rates are affected by local changes in th
 eir structure. Understanding this relationship allows us to tailor the s
 ynthesis of QDs towards a variety of applications. We are particularly i
 nterested in applications such as bioimaging\, super-resolution imaging 
 and FRET and various examples of them will be discussed.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
UID:http://uid.trumba.com/event/197826911
X-TRUMBA-LINK:https://www.washington.edu/calendar/?trumbaEmbed=view%3dev
 ent%26eventid%3d197826911
END:VEVENT
