BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:“Levers of Mastery” Community Lecture
LOCATION:Alder Hall (ALD)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260409T153000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260409T163000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:Al
 der Hall (ALD)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:Alder A
 uditorium
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:Jon Emard\, jmemard@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Lectur
 es/Seminars
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgBzQw5iVGZakij4usa8my1W.jpg
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:Depar
 tment of Civil and Environmental Engineering\, https://www.ce.washington
 .edu/
DTSTAMP:20260330T130804Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Alder Hal
 l (ALD)\nCampus room: Alder Auditorium\nAccessibility Contact: Jon Emard
 \, jmemard@uw.edu\nEvent Types: Lectures/Seminars\nEvent sponsors: Depar
 tment of Civil and Environmental Engineering\,&nbsp\;https://www.ce.wash
 ington.edu/\n&nbsp\;\n\nAbstract\n\nUniversities teach many cognitive sk
 ills designed to launch students into career competence.  But how does o
 ne move from competence to mastery? What skills must be developed for a 
 career to become a true vocation? \n\nIn this lecture\, sculptor\, maste
 r stonemason and CEE Burges Visiting Professor Richard Rhodes reflects o
 n what art and sculpture can teach engineers and architects. How do we n
 urture creativity\, intuition and somatic intelligence to produce master
 ful work? Drawing on his own career at the intersection of engineering a
 nd art\, Rhodes investigates the winding path toward mastery. \n\n\nAbou
 t the speaker\n\nRichard Rhodes is a professional sculptor\, master ston
 emason and scholar of stonework whose career bridges art\, craft and the
  built environment. His work includes public art\, private commissions a
 nd architectural collaboration around the world. He is the author of the
  2025 book “Stone: Ancient Craft to Modern Mastery” and is serving as th
 e 2025-26 Burges Visiting Professor in the UW Department of Civil and En
 vironmental Engineering.\n\nRSVP: https://forms.office.com/r/qQ7J6mL4V5
 \nThis lecture is open to the public. Prior registration is encouraged bu
 t not required.\n\nMore about Richard Rhodes\n	 - Rhodesworks - his desi
 gn studio: https://rhodesworksdesign.com/	\n - Stone: Ancient Craft to M
 odern Mastery - his book: https://rhodesworksdesign.com/education/	\n - 
 Hammer\, chisel\, stone: simple tools for hard moments - his TEDx Seattl
 e talk: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ElfRKvDN7mY&t=5s	\n - Interview 
 with Rick Steves: (FF to minute 13:30P https://soundcloud.com/rick-steve
 s/814-tuesdays-at-the-louvre-stone?utm_source=clipboard&utm_medium=text&
 utm_campaign=social_sharing
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
