SUMMARY:Media\, Power\, and Democracy in South Asia
LOCATION:Student Union Building (HUB)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260410T153000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260410T170000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:St
 udent Union Building (HUB)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:HUB 214
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:sascuw@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Lectur
 es/Seminars
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgA1-%2A1AqENOYkr3xdSvWIfA.jpg
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Target Audience";ID=42285;TYPE=SingleLine:Fre
 e and open to the public
DTSTAMP:20260306T161822Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Student U
 nion Building (HUB)\nCampus room: HUB 214\nAccessibility Contact: sascuw
 @uw.edu\nEvent Types: Lectures/Seminars\nTarget Audience: Free and open 
 to the public\n\nSyeda X cover\n\nWhat does democracy look like from bel
 ow? This talk will look at how ordinary lives are reshaped by surveillan
 ce\, majoritarianism\, and corporate-political nexus in South Asia. Expl
 oring media influence\, gendered surveillance\, majoritarian and casteis
 t politics\, the struggles of urban poor workers and the slow erosion of
  democratic rights in contemporary South Asia through Neha Dixit’s The M
 any Lives of Syeda X\, this talk explores how journalism can recover era
 sed histories\, expose routine violence\, and hold power to account.\n\n
 About the speaker\nNeha Dixit is an independent journalist and author ba
 sed in New Delhi. For over two decades\, she has reported on politics\, 
 gender\, labour\, and social justice in South Asia\, producing investiga
 tive\, narrative\, and long-form journalism for Al Jazeera\, The Washing
 ton Post\, The New York Times\, Caravan\, The Wire\, and others. \n\nHer
  work has exposed extrajudicial killings\, hate crimes\, human trafficki
 ng\, unethical clinical trials\, and sectarian majoritarian violence. Sh
 e has won over a dozen national and international awards\, including the
  International Press Freedom Award (2019) from Committee to Protect Jour
 nalists\, the Chameli Devi Jain Award (2017)\, and the Lorenzo Natali Pr
 ize for Journalism (2011).\n\nHer book\, The Many Lives of Syeda X (Jugg
 ernaut)\, traces 30 years in the life of a migrant Muslim woman navigati
 ng Delhi’s informal labour economy\, holding over 50 jobs without minimu
 m wage. The book\, a vivid portrait of urban India’s invisible workforce
 \, was named Book of the Year 2024 by The Hindu and the Deccan Herald am
 ong others. It won the Ramnath Goenka Sahitya Samman and Kalinga Best De
 but Award and a Special Jury Mention by the CG Moore Prize for Human Rig
 hts Writing.\n\nFree and open to all. At the Jackson School\, opportunit
 ies and events are open to all eligible persons regardless of race\, sex
  or other identity.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
