BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Literary Translator Lecture: Tiffany Tsao\, "Beyond Novelty and 
 Exoticism: Taking the Long View in Translating Indonesian Literature "
LOCATION:Student Union Building (HUB)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T163000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T183000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:St
 udent Union Building (HUB)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:332
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:Simpson Center for the Humanities\, humanities@uw.edu\, 206.543.3920
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Lectur
 es/Seminars
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgD3I2X2ldMT2MGOAyMWUnYa.jpg
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:Spons
 ored by Lee Scheingold\; Simpson Center for the Humanities\; UW’s Transl
 ation Studies Hub\; the Department of Asian Languages & Literature\; Jac
 kson School of International Studies\; Center for Southeast Asia and its
  Diasporas\; Third Place Books.
DTSTAMP:20251024T090634Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Student U
 nion Building (HUB)\nCampus room: 332\nAccessibility Contact: Simpson Ce
 nter for the Humanities\, humanities@uw.edu\, 206.543.3920\nEvent Types:
  Lectures/Seminars\nEvent sponsors: Sponsored by&nbsp\;Lee Scheingold\; 
 Simpson Center for the Humanities\; UW&rsquo\;s Translation Studies Hub
 \; the Department of Asian Languages &amp\; Literature\; Jackson School o
 f International Studies\; Center for Southeast Asia and its Diasporas\; 
 Third Place Books.\n\nTiffany Tsao will discuss the challenges of transl
 ating Indonesian literature in the context of a publishing industry that
  has tended to value Indonesian works more for their “Indonesianness” th
 an their literary value. Catering to a readership interested specificall
 y in the history\, culture\, and living conditions of Indonesia has some
  near-term benefits\, but does this approach do Indonesian writing a dis
 service over the long term? She will discuss\, more specifically\, how t
 his state of affairs has shaped the decisions she has made as a translat
 or - from the works she has chosen to translate\, to her approach to the
  translation process itself.\n\nTiffany Tsao’s translations of Indonesia
 n literature have received the PEN Translation Prize\, the Republic of C
 onsciousness Prize\, and a longlisting for the International Booker Priz
 e. She is also the author of The Majesties (2018) and But Won’t I Miss M
 e (2026)\, and Deputy Editor at the Sydney Review of Books.\n\n*author p
 hoto by Joy Mei En Lai: https://www.joymlai.com/about\n\nGenerously made
  possible by the Lee Scheingold Literary Translator Lecture Fund.\n\nThi
 s event is free and open to the public. Accommodation requests related t
 o a disability or health condition should be made by April 3\, 2026 to t
 he Simpson Center\, 206.543.3920\, schadmin@uw.edu.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
