BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:SHACS: Nikolai Dembrow\, PhD - Cell-type-specific differences in
  excitatory neurons across auditory\, associative\, and motor cortices i
 n non-human primates
LOCATION:Magnuson Health Sciences Center G (HSG)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260416T143000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260416T153000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:Ma
 gnuson Health Sciences Center G (HSG)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:Room G3
 28
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:lfoy@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Academ
 ics\,Lectures/Seminars
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Target Audience";ID=42285;TYPE=SingleLine:Fac
 ulty\, students\, researchers\, lab members
DTSTAMP:20260402T104110Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Magnuson 
 Health Sciences Center G (HSG)\nCampus room: Room G328\nAccessibility Co
 ntact: lfoy@uw.edu\nEvent Types: Academics\,Lectures/Seminars\nTarget Au
 dience: Faculty\, students\, researchers\, lab members\n\nIt has long be
 en known that the cerebral cortex is not a uniform structure. The cellul
 ar composition\, cytoarchitecture\, and connectivity vary across auditor
 y\, motor\, and prefrontal regions. Single-cell RNA sequencing has exten
 ded these regional variations to the level of individual neurons: cortic
 al areas share common cell types\, but those cell types show regional di
 fferences in gene expression. How these specializations contribute to lo
 cal computation remains poorly understood. This talk presents recent wor
 k bridging this gap in primates\, focusing on excitatory pyramidal neuro
 ns\, which possess elaborate dendritic arbors through which they receive
  and integrate synaptic input. Using Patch-seq\, a methodology that simu
 ltaneously captures the transcriptome\, physiology\, and morphology of i
 ndividual neurons\, we examine how gene expression differences relate to
  the morpho-electric properties of these cells in macaque neocortex. Ide
 ntifying which properties are conserved versus divergent between rodents
  and primates\, and which are regionally specialized within the auditory
  cortex\, we seek to provide insights for understanding the circuit-leve
 l underpinnings of complex auditory processing and its dysfunction in di
 sease. \n \n------------------------------------------------------------
 --------------------\n\nNikolai Dembrow\, PhD: \nhttps://gpneuro.uw.edu/
 faculty_profiles/dembrow-nikolai/ is an Associate Professor in UW's Depa
 rtment of Neurobiology & Biophysics.\n \n-------------------------------
 -------------------------------------------------\n\nThe 2025-2026 SHACS
  lectures will all be held in person\, and are free and open to the publ
 ic.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
