BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Public Lecture - Uncertain Empire: Jews\, Nationalism\, and the 
 Fate of British Imperialism
LOCATION:Communications Building (CMU)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260422T163000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260422T180000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:Co
 mmunications Building (CMU)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:120
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:jewishst@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Academ
 ics
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgD%2AJ6GvmDS-qKD0QS-L20yc.jpg
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:The S
 troum Center for Jewish Studies
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Target Audience";ID=42285;TYPE=SingleLine:Ope
 n to public. Registration Required.
DTSTAMP:20260323T101158Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Communica
 tions Building (CMU)\nCampus room: 120\nAccessibility Contact: jewishst@
 uw.edu\nEvent Types: Academics\nEvent sponsors: The Stroum Center for Je
 wish Studies\nTarget Audience: Open to public. Registration Required.\n
 \nJoin us for a talk on Elizabeth E. Imber’s award-winning new book: Unce
 rtain Empire: Jews\, Nationalism\, and the Fate of British Imperialism\n
 \nFollowing the British takeover of Ottoman Palestine\, Jews across the 
 British world found themselves at the center of global political debate.
  This talk explores the complex relationship among British Imperial poli
 cy\, Zionism\, and emerging movements of national self-determination fro
 m 1917 to the establishment of the State of Israel in 1948. In doing so
 \, it shows how the trajectory of British rule became central to Zionist 
 and broader Jewish political thought during a period marked by profound 
 urgency and uncertainty.\n\nElizabeth E. Imber is Associate Professor of
  History and the Michael and Lisa Leffell Chair in Modern Jewish History
  at Clark University. Her work examines the cultural and political dimen
 sions and intersections of Jewish history and European imperial history 
 in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. Her first book\, Uncertain Em
 pire: Jews\, Nationalism\, and the Fate of British Imperialism: \nhttps:
 //www.sup.org/books/jewish-studies/uncertain-empire was published by Sta
 nford University Press in 2025 winning that year’s National Jewish Book 
 Awards - JDC-Herbert Katzki Award (Writing Based on Archival Material).
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
