BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Intergenerational Dialogues: A Workshop for Collaborative Leader
 ship
LOCATION:HUB 334
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260424T100000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260424T123000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
URL:https://earthlab.uw.edu/students/collaborative-leadership-workshops/
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:EarthLab | earthlab@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Worksh
 ops
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Target Audience";ID=42285;TYPE=SingleLine:UW 
 Students
DTSTAMP:20260319T165118Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nAccessibility Contact: Ear
 thLab | earthlab@uw.edu\nEvent Types: Workshops\nTarget Audience: UW Stu
 dents\nLink: https://earthlab.uw.edu/students/collaborative-leadership-w
 orkshops/\n\nWhat if you could learn collaborative leadership skills dir
 ectly from the people shaping environmental decisions in our region?\n\n
 You may want to make a difference on environmental issues—but the bigges
 t breakthroughs rarely happen alone. Whether it’s restoring salmon runs
 \, resolving land-use conflicts\, or protecting ecosystems\, environmenta
 l progress often depends on people who can bring different interests tog
 ether.\n\nThe Collaborative Leadership Program at the Puget Sound Instit
 ute (UW Tacoma) and UW EarthLab invite UW students to a workshop on coll
 aboration and conflict resolution. The workshop will feature interaction
  between students and a panel of accomplished leaders who have collabora
 ted on issues like salmon recovery and Puget Sound restoration. Through 
 interactive exercises\, case studies\, intergenerational dialogues\, and
  small group conversations\, students will learn key concepts and develo
 p collaborative leadership skills they can apply to a wide variety of si
 tuations.\n\nThe workshops are meant as a one-time workshop\, with sever
 al hosted across the region to connect with more students and local case
  studies. The first workshop will be hosted at UW Seattle in Spring 2026
 \, with subsequent workshops to be hosted at UW Bothell and UW Tacoma (F
 all 2026) and The Evergreen State College (Winter 2027). \n\nIntergenera
 tional Dialogues: A Workshop for Collaborative Leadership \nWhen: Friday
 \, April 24\, 2026 - 10am-12:30pm  \nWhere: Husky Union Building — HUB 3
 34 — UW Seattle\nWho: This event is free for all current UW students\, n
 o matter your major or home campus. Please commit to attending the full 
 workshop in person.\n\nThe University of Washington is committed to prov
 iding access and accommodation in its services\, programs and activities
 . To make a request connected to a disability or health condition\, plea
 se contact EarthLab at earthlab@uw.edu by April 8\, 2026.\n\nOutcome goa
 ls: Through attending this workshop\, participants will be exposed to: 
 \n	 - Distinguish zero-sum versus win/win postures and select strategies 
 that increase joint gains 	\n - Practical\, collaborative toolkits (acti
 ve listening\, emotional intelligence practices\, interest-based negotia
 tion\, conflict/dispute resolution\, etc.) 	\n - An exploration of trust
  dynamics and set/reset priorities with partners when things don’t go yo
 ur way 	\n - Case studies to translate to your projects\, (e.g.\, Timber
 /Fish/Wildlife Agreement and Forests & Fish Law\; Boldt Decision/Salmon 
 Co-Management\; Nisqually Watershed Plan\; Yakima Basin Integrated Plan 
 - depending on the region/workshop location) \nLearn more and register:
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
UID:http://uid.trumba.com/event/198815296
X-TRUMBA-LINK:https://www.washington.edu/calendar/?trumbaEmbed=view%3dev
 ent%26eventid%3d198815296
END:VEVENT
