DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Intellect
 ual House (INT)\nAccessibility Contact: natureandhealth@uw.edu\nEvent Ty
 pes: Conferences\,Lectures/Seminars\nEvent sponsors: <a href="https://re
 ifund.org/" target="_blank">REI Cooperative Action Fund</a>\nLink: https
 ://events.uw.edu/8Qd4XR?utm_source=Calendar&utm_campaign=2026Symposium&u
 tm_medium=Trumba\n\nThe UW Center for Nature and Health: \nhttps://natur
 eandhealth.uw.edu/ illuminates the connections between nature and human 
 health and well-being. We work with community and decision-makers to tra
 nslate our findings into programs and policies that ensure everyone can 
 benefit from the healing power of nature.\n\nSince 2016\, we have been h
 osting symposia: \nhttps://natureandhealth.uw.edu/news-and-events/catego
 ry/symposium/ to bring together researchers\, community members\, and de
 cision-makers to learn about new discoveries\, discuss new policies and 
 programs\, and advance partnerships in the field of nature and health. W
 e strive to invite speakers who work hand-in-hand to understand the need
 s of communities who have borne the brunt of social and environmental in
 justices\; who work to address health and access inequities\; and who br
 ing critical insights and perspectives on environmental history as well 
 as outdoor recreation. \n\nINVITED SPEAKERS\n	 - Courtney Aber: \nhttps:
 //events.uw.edu/event/2026NHSymposium/courtney-aber\, national director
 \, Outdoor Initiatives\, YMCA of Greater Seattle\n	The Nature of the Outd
 oors: Stronger Youth Development Through Exploration\n	 	\n - Aileen Cas
 sinetto: \nhttps://events.uw.edu/event/2026NHSymposium/aileen-cassinetto
 \, Laureate Fellow\, Academy of American Poets\n	Building Regenerative a
 nd Equitable Communities Through Poetry\n	 	\n - Sasha Chavez: \nhttps:/
 /events.uw.edu/event/2026NHSymposium/sasha-chavez\, MS\, PhD student\, U
 niversity of Maryland-College Park\n	Community Wellness Spaces and the H
 istory of Parks and Playgrounds\n	 	\n - Anders Rydström: \nhttps://even
 ts.uw.edu/event/2026NHSymposium/agenda\, PhD\, postdoctoral scholar\, Na
 tural Capital Alliance\n	Randomized Controlled Clinical Trial to Study t
 he Effectiveness of Nature Prescriptions \nRESTORATIVE JUSTICE PANEL\n	 
 - Kelli Bush: \nhttps://events.uw.edu/event/2026NHSymposium/kelly-bush\,
  co-director\, Sustainability in Prisons Project	\n - Gabriel S. Galanda
 : \nhttps://events.uw.edu/event/2026NHSymposium/gabriel-s-galanda (Round
  Valley Indian Tribe) managing lawyer\, Galanda Broadman	\n - Ivy Harris
 : \nhttps://events.uw.edu/event/2026NHSymposium/Ivy-Harris\, program man
 ager\, Land Together	\n - Daniel Winterbottom: \nhttps://events.uw.edu/e
 vent/2026NHSymposium/daniel-winterbottom\, RLA\, FASLA\, professor\, UW 
 Landscape Architecture \nSTUDENT & RECENT GRADUATE SPEED TALKS\n	 - Stac
 ey Alfonso: \nhttps://events.uw.edu/event/2026NHSymposium/stacey-alfonso
 \, nature-based curriculum content specialist\n	How Young Children Build
  Relationships With the Natural World Through Their Daily Interactions i
 n an Outdoor Preschool\n	 	\n - Connor Lashus: \nhttps://events.uw.edu/e
 vent/2026NHSymposium/connor-lashus\, PhD student\, UW SEFS\n	The Mechani
 sms by Which Olfaction and Human Microbiomes Mediate or Moderate Effects
  of Natural Environments on Health and Well-Being\n	 	\n - Soteria Li: 
 \nhttps://events.uw.edu/event/2026NHSymposium/soteria-li\, Student\, UW D
 epartment of Psychology\n	Nature Walking\, but Not Urban Walking\, Reduc
 es Depressive Symptoms at One-Month Follow-Up: Interaction Patterns with
  Nature Show Added Benefits for Anxiety and Negative Affect\n	 	\n - Sar
 ah MacFarland: \nhttps://events.uw.edu/event/2026NHSymposium/sarah-chase
 \, research assistant & doctoral student\, UW SEFS\n	Evaluating the Effe
 ctiveness of a Mobile App Designed to Increase Children’s Time in Nature
  and Their Connectedness With Nature\n	 	\n - Jingjing (Tina) Tao: \nhtt
 ps://events.uw.edu/event/2026NHSymposium/jingjing-tina-tao\, research as
 sistant & doctoral student\, UW SEFS\n	Quantifying the Cost Savings of S
 pending Time in Nature in Washington State\n\nAdvanced Registration Requ
 ired: \nhttps://events.uw.edu/8Qd4XR?utm_source=Calendar&utm_campaign=20
 26Symposium&utm_medium=Trumba\n	 - Registration closes on May 15\, 2026.
  There will be no on-site registration.	\n - Registration includes:	\n		
  - Vegetarian and vegan breakfast and lunch		\n - Coffee and tea service
 		\n - Networking reception		\n - 1 drink ticket
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
