BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Kathleen Gutierrez | The B-Sides of Unmaking Botany: Labor and t
 he Archive of the Bereaved in the Colonial Philippines
LOCATION:Thomson Hall (THO)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260501T153000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260501T170000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:Th
 omson Hall (THO)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:THO 317
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:csead@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Lectur
 es/Seminars
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgAb2O5Z1so64hhO8WL0W4LM.jpg
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Target Audience";ID=42285;TYPE=SingleLine:Fre
 e and open to the public
DTSTAMP:20260403T114051Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Thomson H
 all (THO)\nCampus room: THO 317\nAccessibility Contact: csead@uw.edu\nEv
 ent Types: Lectures/Seminars\nTarget Audience: Free and open to the publ
 ic\n\nFree and open to all. At the Jackson School\, opportunities and ev
 ents are open to all eligible persons regardless of race\, sex or other 
 identity. \n\nWriting history entails good editing—and accepting when ma
 terial can’t make the final cut. Lengthy research projects require a com
 mand of sources but also analytical flexibility. Such flexibility can en
 sure rigor sometimes at the expense of findings that\, alas\, must be sh
 elved for some other future use.\n\n“The B-Sides of Unmaking Botany” wil
 l examine a set of sources that did not make it into the recently publis
 hed monograph Unmaking Botany: Science and Vernacular in the Colonial Ph
 ilippines (Duke University Press\, 2025). The objectives of the talk are
  thus twofold: to provide a behind-the-scenes take on the production of 
 a scholarly monograph and to offer a conceptual argument gleaned from th
 e sources that nonetheless resonates with some of Unmaking Botany’s prin
 cipal interventions.\n\nUp to today\, little primary and synthetic infor
 mation exists on Spanish-born\, rank-and-file men recruited to join bota
 ny operations in the colonial Philippines in the late nineteenth century
 . That is\, except for men whose widows compiled extensive documentation
  on their deceased spouses’ lives with the intention of obtaining postmo
 rtem pensions. Paradoxically then\, for many of the rank-and-file of Phi
 lippine colonial botany\, corporeal death meant bureaucratic accretion\;
  loss predicated a paper trail. Widows’ work to put the bureaucratic pie
 ces in place\, so to speak\, open a way to consider those whose labors c
 ontributed to colonial botany’s execution. These women formed a class of
  administrators upon whose work an archive exists and who therefore enab
 le us to contemplate accretion—not just of plants or knowledge\, but of 
 archive—occasioned by death.\n\nAbout the speaker\n\nKathleen "Kat" Cruz
  Gutierrez (Ph.D. Southeast Asian Studies\, Berkeley) is Assistant Profe
 ssor of Southeast Asian history and the history of science at the Univer
 sity of California\, Santa Cruz. She writes on botany\, taxonomies\, and
  the recent scholarly "plant turn." Her research has been generously sup
 ported by the Social Science Research Council\, the Henry Luce Foundatio
 n\, the Mellon Foundation\, and the National Endowment for the Humanitie
 s. Her previous affiliations include De La Salle University\, Manila\, t
 he Humanities Institute of the New York Botanical Garden\, and the Oak S
 pring Garden Foundation. She presently serves as co-Principal Investigat
 or for a community-initiated\, student-engaged research initiative on Fi
 lipino agrarian labor and migration titled "Watsonville is in the Heart.
 " For her work\, she was awarded in 2024 the Richard E. Cone Award for E
 merging Leaders in Community Engagement by LEAD California\, a biannual 
 honor that recognizes a single person in higher education evidencing ste
 adfast commitment to community engagement in their early career.
