BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Public Lecture | Have You Heard? Black Buddhism Through the Lens
  of Tina Turner | Dr. Ralph H. Craig III
LOCATION:Student Union Building (HUB)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260504T150000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260504T163000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:St
 udent Union Building (HUB)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:HUB 250
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:relig@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Academ
 ics
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgCFVxKFr8XG1nvL1JYoVTYE.jpg
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:UW Ja
 ckson School-Religious Studies Program\, Asian Languages & Literatures\,
  Buddhist Studies Program
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Target Audience";ID=42285;TYPE=SingleLine:Ope
 n to public. Registration required.
DTSTAMP:20260324T145551Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Student U
 nion Building (HUB)\nCampus room: HUB 250\nAccessibility Contact: relig@
 uw.edu\nEvent Types: Academics\nEvent sponsors: UW Jackson School-Religi
 ous Studies Program\, Asian Languages &amp\; Literatures\, Buddhist Stud
 ies Program\nTarget Audience: Open to public. Registration required.\n\n
 Join us for an afternoon lecture on May 4th in HUB 250 featuring Dr. Ral
 ph H. Craig III on Black Buddhism Through the Lens of Tina Turner. A lig
 ht reception will be provided. \n\nTina Turner's (1939-2023) successful 
 recording career and electrifying stage performances earned her the moni
 ker of “Queen of Rock and Roll.” At the same time\, Turner was perhaps o
 ne of the most famous Black Buddhist celebrities. In this talk\, I will 
 highlight the ways that Turner's Buddhist practice combined her Afro-Pro
 testant upbringing\, the trans-Atlantic flow of metaphysical religious i
 deas\, and SGI Nichiren Buddhism. The talk will show how Turner's combin
 atory religious sensibilities are indicative of trends in Black Buddhism
 .\n\ncraig_III_ralph_900sq\nRalph H. Craig III is an Assistant Professor
  of Religion at Whitman College. He is an interdisciplinary scholar of r
 eligion whose research focuses on South Asian Buddhism and American Budd
 hism. His first book\, Dancing in My Dreams: A Spiritual Biography of Ti
 na Turner (Eerdmans Publishing\, 2023)\, explores the place of religion 
 in the life and career of Tina Turner and examines her development as a 
 Black Buddhist teacher. His next book project is a monograph on preacher
 s in ca. 1st century BCE-6th century CE Buddhist sūtras.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
