BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:“Japan’s Democracy in an Age of Uncertainty” with Tobias Harris
 \, 2026 Griffith and Patricia Way Lecture
LOCATION:Kane Hall (KNE)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260504T173000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260504T190000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:Ka
 ne Hall (KNE)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:Kane Ha
 ll 225 | reception to follow
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:To request disability accommodation\, contact the Disability Services
  Office at 206.543.6450 (voice)\, 206.543.6452 (TTY) or email at dso@uw.
 edu. The UW makes every effort to honor accommodation requests. Requests
  can be responded to most effectively if received as far in advance of t
 he event as possible\, preferably at least 10 days.
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Lectur
 es/Seminars\,Special Events
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgAXIEnuJRMR-mN%2AKP9wH0RQ.jpg
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:Spons
 ored by the UW Japan Studies Program and made possible by the Griffith a
 nd Patricia Way Lecture endowment. : \nhttps://jsis.washington.edu/japan
 /events/griffith-and-patricia-way-lecture-series/
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Target Audience";ID=42285;TYPE=SingleLine:Fre
 e and open to the public. Registration IS OPEN
DTSTAMP:20260330T155952Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Kane Hall
  (KNE)\nCampus room: Kane Hall 225 | reception to follow\nAccessibility 
 Contact: To request disability accommodation\, contact the Disability Se
 rvices Office at 206.543.6450 (voice)\, 206.543.6452 (TTY) or email at d
 so@uw.edu. The UW makes every effort to honor accommodation requests. Re
 quests can be responded to most effectively if received as far in advanc
 e of the event as possible\, preferably at least 10 days.\nEvent Types: 
 Lectures/Seminars\,Special Events\nEvent sponsors: Sponsored by the <str
 ong>UW Japan Studies Program</strong> and made possible by the <a href="
 https://jsis.washington.edu/japan/events/griffith-and-patricia-way-lectu
 re-series/" target="_blank">Griffith and Patricia Way Lecture endowment.
 &nbsp\;</a>\nTarget Audience: Free and open to the public. Registration 
 IS OPEN\n\nThe Way Lecture is celebrating its 19th year! Join us May 4th
 \, 2026 for a talk by Tobias Harris\, Founder and Principal of Japan For
 esight LLC.\n\nThe foundation of the Abe consensus — the LDP\, together 
 with Komeito\, governing with large\, stable majorities to promote growt
 h as part of the global economy and develop Japan’s military power and i
 nternational partnerships under the aegis of US leadership — has crumble
 d after little more than a decade. The LDP has lost public trust\, its r
 elationship with Komeito\, and its large majorities. The US is in retrea
 t and no longer defending the international order from which Japan had b
 enefited. This talk will look at how this order crumbled and where Japan
 ’s politics goes from here.\n\nHarris has observed Japan as a political 
 risk analyst at Teneo Intelligence and as a researcher at universities a
 nd think tanks. He is also Senior Advisor for Japan at Aurora Macro Stra
 tegies. For two decades\, he has written about Japan’s politics and the 
 geopolitics of Asia for major world publications\, including The New Yor
 k Times\, Washington Post\, Wall Street Journal\, and the Financial Time
 s. He comments regularly about Japan on television and radio broadcasts.
  He is the author of The Iconoclast: Shinzō Abe and the New Japan (Hurst
  Publishers 2020). An updated paperback edition was published in October
  2023. A native of Chicago\, he now lives outside of Washington\, DC wit
 h his family.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
