BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:CAMP LECTURE | “Against the North as well as the South\, Abraham
  Lincoln as well as Jefferson Davis”: The Civil Wars of Lucy Broaddus\, 
 Frederick Douglass\, and Franz Sigel | Angela Zimmerman\, George Washing
 ton University
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260506T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260506T173000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:histmain@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Lectur
 es/Seminars
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:The S
 tephanie Camp Memorial Lecture is sponsored by the Departments of Histor
 y and Gender\, Women's\, and Sexuality Studies (GWSS)\, The Harry Bridge
 s Center for Labor Studies\, and The Simpson Center for the Humanities.
DTSTAMP:20260127T114832Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nAccessibility Contact: his
 tmain@uw.edu\nEvent Types: Lectures/Seminars\nEvent sponsors: The Stepha
 nie Camp Memorial Lecture is sponsored by the Departments of History and
  Gender\, Women&#39\;s\, and Sexuality Studies (GWSS)\,&nbsp\;The Harry 
 Bridges Center for Labor Studies\, and The Simpson Center for the Humani
 ties.\n\n“If we fight\, we must fight against the North as well as the S
 outh\, Abraham Lincoln as well as Jefferson Davis\,” Frederick Douglass 
 declared in May 1861\, just a few weeks after the Civil War began. His s
 tatement suggests a very different Civil War than the we usually hear ab
 out\, centered on Abraham Lincoln: a war for the Union giving way to a t
 entative emancipation within the bounds of the law\, the constitution\, 
 and private property.\n\nOccluded in such conventional narratives are st
 ruggles over white supremacy\, the extent of Black freedom\, capitalism
 \, and patriotic nationalism. We get an entirely different war - not just
  a different interpretation of that war -- if we center radical perspect
 ives that aimed for freedoms anathema to Union and Confederacy alike.  I
 n this talk I will look at the Civil War as it was understood by Lucy Br
 oaddus\, a woman born into slavery in Missouri in 1862\, Frederick Dougl
 ass\, and Franz Sigel\, a communist German refugee who served as a gener
 al in the Union Army. Each presents a different war\, with different aim
 s\, different enemies\, and different chronologies. Together they reveal
  struggles for freedoms that Lincoln and the histories sharing his persp
 ective have worked to contain and obscure.\n \n\n-----------------------
 ---------------------------------------------------------\n\nAngela Elis
 abeth Zimmerman is professor of history at George Washington University.
  Her recent research has focused on the global history of the U.S. Civil
  War\, Reconstruction\, and the New South. She is the author of Alabama 
 in Africa: Booker T. Washington\, the German Empire\, and the Globalizat
 ion of the New South (Princeton\, 2010) and the editor of Karl Marx and 
 Friedrich Engels\, The Civil War in the United States (International Pub
 lishers\, 2016). Her first book\, Anthropology and Antihumanism in Imper
 ial Germany (Chicago\, 2001)\, studied imperialism\, science\, and popul
 ar culture. Her next book\, To Seek a Newer World\, will be published by
  Alfred A. Knopf in 2027.\n \n\n----------------------------------------
 ----------------------------------------\n\nThe Stephanie Camp Memorial 
 Lecture was established to honor the memory of our beloved colleague\, S
 tephanie M.H. Camp\, who was the Donald W. Logan Family Endowed Chair in
  American History and the author of the award-winning book Closer to Fre
 edom: Enslaved Women and Everyday Resistance in the Plantation South (20
 04). Her work remains a powerful influence on the fields of race\, gende
 r\, and slavery in and beyond American history.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
