BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Firearms and Public Health in Seattle’s East African Heritage Co
 mmunities
LOCATION:Thomson Hall (THO)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260511T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260511T180000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:Th
 omson Hall (THO)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:sameerai@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Lectur
 es/Seminars
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Target Audience";ID=42285;TYPE=SingleLine:Fre
 e and open to the public
DTSTAMP:20260402T165355Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Thomson H
 all (THO)\nAccessibility Contact: sameerai@uw.edu\nEvent Types: Lectures
 /Seminars\nTarget Audience: Free and open to the public\n\nFree and open
  to all. At the Jackson School\, opportunities and events are open to al
 l eligible persons regardless of race\, sex or other identity. \n\nThe g
 reater Seattle metropolitan area is home to a large\, thriving populatio
 n of people of East African heritage\, including local Ethiopian\, Eritr
 ean\, and Somali Americans. While these communities have much to celebra
 te\, they also face a variety of common American social and economic pro
 blems\, including gun violence.  In this panel\, two University of Washi
 ngton graduate students\, Hiwot Weldemariam and Meron Girma\, will speak
  about their research conducted in association with the University of Wa
 shington’s Center for Firearm Injury Prevention\, which is part of UW Me
 dicine. The panel\, organized by UW African Studies and the UW Horn of A
 frica Initiative\, is free and open to the public\; anyone interested in
  these communities is welcome to attend. \n\nAbout the panelists\n\nHiwo
 t Weldemariam is a PhD student in Epidemiology at the University of Wash
 ington School of Public Health and a predoctoral research associate at t
 he University of Washington Center for Firearm Injury Prevention. She ea
 rned a Master of Public Health in Epidemiology from the University of Wa
 shington and a Master of Public Policy from Japan. Her research focuses 
 on firearm violence\, mental health\, substance use\, and healthcare uti
 lization. She aspires to advance health equity\, improve access to care
 \, and promote better health outcomes among immigrant and historically un
 derrepresented communities through her research.\n \nMeron Girma\, is a 
 medical student in the UW School of Medicine and a Research Project Mana
 ger for the Center of Firearm Injury Prevention. Prior to UW\, she obtai
 ned her master's in public health from Yale University\, concentrating i
 n Global Health and US Health Justice. As a qualitative researcher she i
 s deeply passionate about using research as a way to amplify the stories
  of families and youth impacted by violence particularly in African immi
 grant populations while examining culturally appropriate strategies for 
 prevention and intervention.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
