BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:What Is Troubling Josephus in the Contra Apionem? Comparative Na
 rrative Approaches to the Question of Antisemitism in Antiquity
LOCATION:Thomson Hall (THO)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260518T153000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260518T170000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:Th
 omson Hall (THO)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:THO 317
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:sameerai@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Lectur
 es/Seminars
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgDwnKbvEGL6yc5fV0skvANT.jpg
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:Afric
 an Studies Program\, Stroum Center for Jewish Studies\, Middle Eastern L
 anguages and Cultures
DTSTAMP:20260227T132007Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Thomson H
 all (THO)\nCampus room: THO 317\nAccessibility Contact: sameerai@uw.edu
 \nEvent Types: Lectures/Seminars\nEvent sponsors: African Studies Program
 \, Stroum Center for Jewish Studies\, Middle Eastern Languages and Cultu
 res&nbsp\;\n\nFree and open to all. At the Jackson School\, opportunitie
 s and events are open to all eligible persons regardless of race\, sex o
 r other identity. \n\n\nThe term antisemitism continues to resist schola
 rly attempts to define or historicize it. Definitions of antisemitism ar
 e numerous\, varied and at times conflicting. Similar conflicts of inter
 pretation characterize scholarly attempts to define and historicize the 
 categories of race and racism\, particularly in historiographies of the 
 premodern past. In this paper\, I propose the utility of comparative nar
 rative analysis as one mode of mitigating the problems of definition and
  translation that arise when considering the ancient past through the pr
 ism of modern categories. I then provide a case study by analyzing Josep
 hus’s first-century Contra Apionem in light of certain narrative motifs 
 that appear in racializing discourses circulating in nineteenth-century 
 America. Comparative narrative analysis of Josephus's work illustrates t
 hat the author has a different set of concerns he wants to address in hi
 s defense of Jews than the issues traditionally highlighted by the schol
 arship on antisemitism in antiquity.\n\nAbout the speaker\nYonatan Binya
 m is an Assistant Professor of Ancient Mediterranean and Ethiopic Studie
 s in the Department of Middle Eastern Languages and Cultures at the Univ
 ersity of California\, Berkeley
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
