SUMMARY:FOOD SYSTEMS SEMINAR:  State-Level Food Security Data in Action:
  Insights from Washington State's WAFOOD Survey
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260527T133000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260527T142000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
URL:https://foodsystems.uw.edu/seminar/
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:Check M
 y Plan for location
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:nutr@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Lectur
 es/Seminars
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:Schoo
 l of Public Health Food Systems\, Nutrition\, and Health program
DTSTAMP:20260320T104404Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus room: Check My Plan
  for location\nAccessibility Contact: nutr@uw.edu\nEvent Types: Lectures
 /Seminars\nEvent sponsors: School of Public Health Food Systems\, Nutrit
 ion\, and Health program\nLink: https://foodsystems.uw.edu/seminar/\n\nS
 tate-Level Food Security Data in Action: Insights from Washington State'
 s WAFOOD Survey\n\nSpeakers:\n\n	 - Marie Spiker\, assistant professor\,
  Epidemiology\, core faculty\, FSNH\, UW\;	\n - Jennifer Otten\, profess
 or\, DEOHS\; undergraduate program director and core faculty\, FSNH\, UW
 \n\nThis session is offered as part of the weekly series on: "Food and N
 utrition Security: Understanding\, Measuring and Reimagining Nutrition A
 ssistance in the U.S."\n\nIf you care about how food-related safety nets
  succeed—or fail—this seminar offers tools to understand today’s landsca
 pe and imagine a better one.\n\nHow is food and nutrition security defin
 ed\, measured\, and funded in the United States—and how do those choices
  shape real‑world hunger and health?\n\nThis seminar explores the nation
 ’s major nutrition assistance programs—SNAP\, WIC\, school meals\, and t
 he charitable food system. Learn how these programs work\, who they reac
 h\, and why their impacts vary across states and communities.\n\nAll UW 
 students\, faculty\, and staff are welcome to attend the seminar. Check 
 MyPlan for location information.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
