 ment of Comparative History of Ideas (CHID)\, Department of German Studi
 es\, The Walter Chapin Simpson Center for the Humanities\, The Graduate 
 School\nLink: https://www.washington.edu/lectures/events/is-a-river-aliv
 e-exploring-the-lives-deaths-and-rights-of-rivers-presented-by-the-offic
 e-of-public-lectures/\n\nFlow into a radical reimagining of rivers—as se
 ntient beings with rights. This global lecture blends activism\, art\, a
 nd law to reveal how river justice shapes our survival in a world where 
 water is more than resource—it’s kin.\n\nIn person is SOLD OUT. Livestre
 aming is available for registration.
