BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Sea Change Within Us: Presented by Karin Stevens Dance
LOCATION:Gould Hall (GLD)
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260528T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260528T173000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
URL:https://forms.gle/DfCjWpaFjxre4DSNA
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus location";ID=30032;TYPE=CustomAsset:Go
 uld Hall (GLD)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:EarthLab | earthlab@uw.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Perfor
 mances
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:Washi
 ngton Sea Grant\nEarthLab\nKarin Stevens Dance\nFunded by the National O
 ceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA)
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Target Audience";ID=42285;TYPE=SingleLine:UW 
 students\, faculty and staff
DTSTAMP:20260327T140035Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus location: Gould Hal
 l (GLD)\nAccessibility Contact: EarthLab | earthlab@uw.edu\nEvent Types:
  Performances\nEvent sponsors: Washington Sea Grant\nEarthLab\nKarin Ste
 vens Dance\nFunded by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administratio
 n (NOAA)\nTarget Audience: UW students\, faculty and staff\nLink: https:
 //forms.gle/DfCjWpaFjxre4DSNA\n\nSea Change Within Us\, a recreated 2019
  project by Karin Stevens Dance\, is a sixty-minute performance that add
 resses local Washington state water issues and the consequences of clima
 te change\, using the voices of real people we interviewed\, combined wi
 th moving rigid structures of water images by dancing human bodies.\n\nE
 ight dancers move four large panels into dynamic configurations to explo
 re themes such as rivers and dams\, endangered wild Pacific salmon and S
 outhern Resident Orca\, melting ice\, sea-level rise\, flooding\, migrat
 ion\, injustices to Indigenous fishing rights\, divisive politics\, and 
 the complexities of human dis/re/connection. Amid these turbulent themat
 ic layers\, grief is embodied in the “Rivers\, Dams\, Salmon\, Orca” sec
 tion through the actual cries of mother orca Tahlequah. A call to collec
 tive awareness emerges in the section “Descending Pressure\,” echoing th
 e repeated phrase of a climate activist-artist: “Our bodies are a source
  of wisdom.”\n\nLearn more about the program here: https://www.karinstev
 ensdance.com/currentwork/2026/1/26/sea-change-within-us-program\n\nThis 
 event is currently open to UW students\, faculty and staff. Space is lim
 ited and registration is required.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
UID:http://uid.trumba.com/event/199658791
X-TRUMBA-LINK:https://www.washington.edu/calendar/?trumbaEmbed=view%3dev
 ent%26eventid%3d199658791
END:VEVENT
