BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Causal Inference with Observational Data: Common Designs and Sta
 tistical Methods - Summer Institutes Online Short Course
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260707T083000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260707T120000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
URL:https://si.biostat.washington.edu/institutes/siscer/CR2602
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:Online
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:Deb Nelson\, nelsod6@uw.edu\, 206-685-9323
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Specia
 l Events\,Workshops
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:UW Bi
 ostatistics
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Target Audience";ID=42285;TYPE=SingleLine:Tar
 get audiences for this module are: 1. clinical researchers who need to u
 se observational data to
DTSTAMP:20260319T141807Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus room: Online\nAcces
 sibility Contact: Deb Nelson\, nelsod6@uw.edu\, 206-685-9323\nEvent Type
 s: Special Events\,Workshops\nEvent sponsors: UW Biostatistics\nTarget A
 udience: Target audiences for this module are: 1. clinical researchers w
 ho need to use observational data to\nLink: https://si.biostat.washingto
 n.edu/institutes/siscer/CR2602\n\nObservational studies are non-interven
 tional empirical investigations of causal effects and are playing an inc
 reasingly vital role in healthcare decision making in the era of data sc
 ience. The study design is particularly important in planning observatio
 nal studies due to the lack of randomization. Aspects of design include 
 defining the objectives and context under investigation\, collecting the
  right data\, and choosing suitable strategies to remove bias from measu
 red and unmeasured confounders. Statistical analysis should also align w
 ith the design.\n\nThis module covers key concepts and useful methods fo
 r designing and analyzing observational studies. The first part of the m
 odule will focus on matching and weighting methods for cohort and case-c
 ontrol studies for causal inference. Specific topics include basic tools
  of matching and weighting\, randomization inference\, and sensitivity a
 nalysis. The second part of the module will focus on methods to address 
 unmeasured confounding via causal exclusion. Specific topics include ins
 trumental variables\, negative controls\, and difference-in-differences.
  Participants will also gain practical experience by applying these meth
 ods to real datasets using R.
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
