X-TRUMBA-LINK:https://www.washington.edu/calendar/?trumbaEmbed=view%3dev
 ent%26eventid%3d199032172
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Design and Analysis of Clinical Trials - Summer Institutes Onlin
 e Short Course
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260707T083000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260709T123000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
URL:https://si.biostat.washington.edu/institutes/siscer/CR2601
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Generic UW Even
 t
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event interval";ID=30051;TYPE=CustomAsset:Sin
 gle day event
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus room";ID=28429;TYPE=SingleLine:Online
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Accessibility Contact";ID=62969;TYPE=SingleLi
 ne:Deb Nelson\, nelsod6@uw.edu\, 206-685-9323
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Types";ID=30073;TYPE=CustomAsset:Specia
 l Events\,Workshops
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event sponsors";ID=30383;TYPE=MultiLine:UW Bi
 ostatistics
DTSTAMP:20260319T141648Z
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nCampus room: Online\nAcces
 sibility Contact: Deb Nelson\, nelsod6@uw.edu\, 206-685-9323\nEvent Type
 s: Special Events\,Workshops\nEvent sponsors: UW Biostatistics\nLink: ht
 tps://si.biostat.washington.edu/institutes/siscer/CR2601\n\nThe design a
 nd analysis of a randomized clinical trial involves a series of decision
 s\, including the choice of the primary outcome\, sample size\, randomiz
 ation algorithm\, interim monitoring plan\, and the choice of the primar
 y analysis and estimand of interest. This course will focus on the stati
 stical considerations that inform each of these decisions.  Additional t
 opics include addressing multiple comparisons\, handling missing data\, 
 and whether to consider an adaptive design. We will present a set of sim
 ple tools and principles that go a long way towards defining a robust cl
 inical trial design. We will also shed light on some common pitfalls to 
 avoid. Discussions will be driven by examples of trials from a variety o
 f domains including cardiovascular disease\, infectious disease (HIV\, E
 bola\, COVID-19)\, as well as other settings.\n\nWe assume enrollees wil
 l be familiar with topics taught in introductory statistics (t-tests\, r
 egression\, confidence intervals\, p-values\, and a basic understanding 
 of the central limit theorem).
CATEGORIES:UW Seattle Campus Events
